# Component Structure and Naming

- Place components in `src/components/[ComponentName]/[ComponentName].tsx`
- Place pages in `src/pages/[PageName]/[PageName]Page.tsx`
- Place forms in `src/pages/[PageName]/[PageName]Form.tsx` or `src/components/forms/[ComponentName]/[ComponentName].tsx`
- Use PascalCase for component files and folders
- Default export for components, named exports for utilities
- Colocate component-specific styles as `[ComponentName].scss` in same directory

# Component Implementation

- Use functional components only, never class components
- Import React: `import React from 'react';`
- Import Hookstate hooks at top: `import { useState } from "@hookstate/core";`
- Use Hookstate plugins: `Validation`, `Initial`, `Touched` for forms
- Attach plugins after state creation: `formState.attach(Validation)`
- Call hooks at component top level, never conditionally

# State Management

- Use Hookstate for global state: `createState<T>()` for globals, `useState(globalState)` for consumption
- Place global state modules in `src/state/[domain]/[domain]-state.ts`
- Export `use[Domain]State()` hooks that wrap state access
- Create service classes (e.g., `DashboardUserService`) to encapsulate state logic
- Use `useState<T>()` for local component state when state doesn't need sharing
- Never mutate state directly; always use `.set()` or `.merge()`
- Check if state modified via `Initial(formState.field).modified()`

# Form Handling

- Create form state with Hookstate: `const formState = useState<FormData>({ ... })`
- Attach plugins: `Validation`, `Initial`, `Touched`
- Define validators using `Validation(formState.field).validate(validator, errorMsg, 'error')`
- Import validators from `src/utils/validation-utils.ts`: `validateEmail`, `validateRequiredString`, `validateStringLength`
- Check validation: `failsHookstateValidation(formState.field)`, `Validation(formState).valid()`
- Track dirty state: `isFormModified()` checks `Initial(formState.field).modified()`
- Disable forms on success: check `props.successAction?.success`
- Use controlled inputs: `value={formState.field.get()}`, `onChange={e => formState.field.set(e.target.value)}`
- Prevent default on submit: `event.preventDefault()` in `onSubmit`
- Use form components: `<Form>`, `<FormGroup>`, `<TextInput>`, `<Checkbox>`, `<SubmitActions>`, `<SuccessErrorMessage>`
- Pass validation errors to FormGroup: `isError={failsHookstateValidation(formState.field)}`, `errorMessages={generateStringErrorMessages(formState.field)}`

# API Calls

- Always use generated OpenAPI client from `src/openapi/`
- Import APIs: `import { DashboardUserControllerApi } from '../../openapi/apis/dashboard-user-controller-api'`
- Import DTOs: `import { DashboardUserDto } from '../../openapi/models'`
- Instantiate APIs with `globalOpenapiConfig`: `new DashboardUserControllerApi(globalOpenapiConfig.configuration, globalOpenapiConfig.basePath, globalOpenapiConfig.axios)`
- Never use raw `fetch()` or create raw axios instances
- Wrap API calls in service methods, not in components
- Handle cancellation: use `makeCancellableDataRequest()` for requests
- Handle errors: use `prepareDataCrudErrorResponse(error)` from `src/state/data-service/data-service-utils.ts`

# TypeScript

- Never use `any` type; use specific types or generics
- Never use `@ts-ignore` without a comment explaining why
- Prefer discriminated unions over enums where appropriate
- Use `interface` for object shapes, `type` for unions/aliases
- Import generated types from `src/openapi/models`
- Define props interfaces: `interface [ComponentName]Props { ... }`
- Use optional chaining: `props.data?.id` instead of `props.data && props.data.id`
- Use nullish coalescing: `props.data?.id ?? ""` instead of ternaries where appropriate
- Export types alongside components when reusable

# Styling

- Use SCSS modules colocated with components: `ComponentName.scss`
- Import styles: `import './ComponentName.scss';`
- Use USWDS components from `@trussworks/react-uswds`
- Import USWDS styles in component: `@import "~uswds/dist/scss/..."`
- Use existing USWDS utility classes where possible
- Prefix custom classes with component/domain name to avoid collisions
- Use Bootstrap Grid for layout (already imported globally)
- Never use inline styles (`style={{ ... }}`)
- Use semantic class names: `.dashboard-user-form`, `.tron-form`, not `.blue-button`

# Testing

- Place tests in `__tests__` directory adjacent to component
- Name test files: `[ComponentName].test.tsx` or `[filename].test.ts`
- Import from `@testing-library/react`: `render`, `fireEvent`, `screen`
- Import from `@testing-library/jest-dom` for matchers
- Use `describe()` blocks to group related tests
- Use `beforeEach()` for setup, mock functions with `jest.fn()`
- Use `data-testid` attributes for querying elements
- Mock OpenAPI services in tests
- Cover happy path, validation errors, submission success/failure

# What NOT to Do

- No inline styles (`style={{ ... }}`)
- No business logic in JSX; extract to functions
- No `fetch()` outside the generated API client
- No class components
- No direct state mutation
- No conditional hook calls
- No `any` type without strong justification
- No `@ts-ignore` without explanatory comment
- No raw axios instances; use `globalOpenapiConfig.axios`
- No styles in JS; use SCSS files
- No hardcoded API URLs; use `Config.API_BASE_URL`
- No test files next to source files; use `__tests__/` directory
